      More Left
   =20
 =20
We talked on Friday
  [2]
 about Andrew Left, the activist short seller=C2=A0who was charged with sec=
urities fraud last week. The US Securities and Exchange Commission and Depa=
rtment of Justice alleged that Left frequently shorted stocks, published re=
search reports and tweets saying he was short, and then more or less immedi=
ately covered his shorts: The stocks would drop on his tweets, and he would=
 buy them back at a quick profit rather than waiting to see if his short re=
ports were correct and the stocks stayed down.As I wrote on Friday: That se=
ems fine? I mean, it would be fine if Left was explicit about it, and also =
probably fine if he was, you know, implicit about it. Put some fine print i=
n the reports saying =E2=80=9Cwe can cover at any time,=E2=80=9D leave it a=
t that, take some profits. But what annoys the authorities is that Left all=
egedly=C2=A0lied=C2=A0about it, telling people on Twitter and television th=
at he was still short even after he had covered.=C2=A0I can see why this wo=
uld be=C2=A0annoying, and fraud. But it strikes me as=C2=A0a secondary issu=
e; to me, the primary issue is: Was he right? Like, if he published short r=
eports saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is a fraud,=E2=80=9D and then the stock dr=
opped, and then he covered his shorts, and then a few months later Company =
X was shut down for fraud, then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I would be inclined to give =
him the benefit of the doubt? Even if he was lying about still being short?=
Because I think the point here is that it=E2=80=99s securities fraud if he =
deceived people about some=C2=A0material=C2=A0fact. If people went around t=
hinking =E2=80=9CI need to be in the same trades Andrew Left,=E2=80=9D and =
he said =E2=80=9CI shorted Company X and am still short right this minute a=
nd will stay short for months,=E2=80=9D and they believed him=C2=A0about hi=
s position, so they=C2=A0shorted Company X, and actually he had already bou=
ght back his short, then that would be fraud about a material fact.But I do=
n=E2=80=99t think that happened? I think that happened is that people went =
around thinking =E2=80=9CAndrew Left has a good track record of finding sto=
cks to short,=E2=80=9D and he said =E2=80=9CCompany X is a fraud and I am s=
hort,=E2=80=9D and they believed him=C2=A0about Company X, so they shorted =
Company X. And then if he was honest and diligent and mostly correct about =
Company X being a fraud, then, you know, kind of no harm no foul? Even if h=
e covered his shorts immediately?I am not saying this is the law =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just a statem=
ent of my sympathies. And I have not closely studied his track record, and =
I don=E2=80=99t know how honest and diligent his calls actually were; again=
, the SEC has messages that suggest he might not have been all that honest =
and diligent. But we did talk about one call, when Left decided to short a =
Canadian cannabis company called Cronos Group in 2018. =E2=80=9CI have a ho=
t voice in cannibas,=E2=80=9D Left told an associate; =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99=
s take a vantage [sic] of it.=E2=80=9D
  [3]
=C2=A0So, says the SEC:Later that same day, Left published a report and sen=
t a tweet to his readers recommending that they sell CRON and that the true=
 valuation of the company was $3.50 per share: =E2=80=9C$CRON tgt price $3.=
5. Everything that is contaminated about the Cannabis space. ALL HYPE with =
possible securities fraud.=E2=80=9D The tweet linked to the report which wa=
s titled, =E2=80=9CCronos: The Dark Side of The Cannabis Space.=E2=80=9DI w=
rote:Weirdly the SEC does not get into this, but Cronos closed at $12.74 pe=
r share on Aug. 29, 2018, the day before Left=E2=80=99s report. It closed a=
t $9.12 on Aug. 30, after the report came out, a 28% drop. It then rallied,=
 getting as high as $23.70 in March 2019. But then it mostly went down. It =
hit Left=E2=80=99s $3.50 price target in early 2022, and closed at $2.42 ye=
sterday. It has never reported an operating profit. It took a while, and ma=
ny readers who shorted the stock presumably lost money, but was Left =E2=80=
=A6 right?But somehow I missed that=C2=A0the SEC charged Cronos with fraud=
=C2=A0in 2022. It=E2=80=99s not the biggest fraud in the world, and it happ=
ened starting in 2019 (so after Left=E2=80=99s report), but still. The SEC =
says that Left was committing fraud when he said that Cronos would go to $3=
.50 and might be committing securities fraud, even though Cronos went to $3=
.50 and (in the SEC=E2=80=99s view) committed=C2=A0securities fraud.=C2=A0O=
ne other point. The SEC charges against Left allege that he basically did s=
ome pump-and-dumps (buy stocks, say misleading things to get others to buy =
them, sell into the demand), and =E2=80=94=C2=A0more characteristically, fo=
r a short seller=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0some reverse pump-and-dumps (short sto=
cks, say misleading things to get others to sell them, buy into the demand)=
. (The latter trade is sometimes called =E2=80=9Cshort and distort,=E2=80=
=9D to have another rhyme.) This is a very traditional thing to charge a me=
dia-happy investor with, and the SEC brings lots of cases like this.But we =
did talk a few months ago about a very weird case in Texas where a federal =
district judge ruled that actually pump-and-dumps are legal =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
they are not securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0because the government can=E2=
=80=99t prove that the pump-and-dumper=C2=A0deceived=C2=A0the same people t=
hat he=C2=A0took money=C2=A0from. A pump-and-dumper tells lies about a stoc=
k to induce people to buy the stock, and then he sells the stock. But you c=
an=E2=80=99t prove =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in fact it is unlikely =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that he sells the stock=C2=A0to=C2=A0the people he lied to. Probably the=
 pump-and-dumper sells stock to market makers, and his deceived readers buy=
 stock from the market makers, so the pump-and-dumper =E2=80=9Cdid not obta=
in something of value from the entity to be deceived=E2=80=9D and so did no=
t defraud anyone.I wrote about the decision at the time, but I have tried n=
ot to think about it much since, because (1) it is obviously wrong but (2) =
if you believe it, then pretty much=C2=A0all public-markets=C2=A0securities=
 fraud is legal now,
  [4]
=C2=A0because all public-market securities fraud works like that: You never=
 trade=C2=A0directly=C2=A0with the people you=E2=80=99re lying to, so you c=
an =E2=80=94=C2=A0on this theory =E2=80=94=C2=A0never defraud anyone. But a=
 reader emailed to mention that case and ask =E2=80=9Cwhat is different abo=
ut the two cases,=E2=80=9D and the answer is nothing. If that ruling is cor=
rect then nothing, including this, is fraud.
