</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a big oil company looking t=
o get into the renewable energy business, how do you know what to do? How d=
o you learn how to make renewable fuels and market them to consumers? One p=
ossible approach is pure introspection:=C2=A0Get all your existing oil engi=
neers and executives in a room and say =E2=80=9Cthink about renewables=E2=
=80=9D until you have a renewables business. (Perhaps have them read the pu=
blic literature on renewables businesses first.)=C2=A0I am sure that in som=
e contexts this approach works =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s probably how a l=
ot of financial firms get into a lot of new businesses? =E2=80=94 but it se=
ems hard.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More realistically, you are going=
 to be building on somebody else=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0some competitor=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0work. One way to do that is to=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0=
</em>the competitor: You call up a renewables company that seems good, you =
say =E2=80=9Chey we would like to buy you at a premium,=E2=80=9D they say =
=E2=80=9Csure sounds great,=E2=80=9D you hand them a wad of cash and now yo=
u have a renewables business.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There a=
re other ways. You can=C2=A0<em>hire=C2=A0</em>some people from existing re=
newables companies and get them to build a renewables business for you. Thi=
s might cause trouble: They might have noncompete agreements, or confidenti=
ality agreements, and if they use the=C2=A0renewables knowledge they gained=
 their old jobs to build your business, they (and you) might get sued. It c=
an be hard to know what is a protected trade secret and what is portable in=
dustry knowledge.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you can call up =
some existing renewables companies and say =E2=80=9Chey we would also like =
to get into renewables, can you give us some advice?=E2=80=9D But they migh=
t say no. You are, after all, a potential competitor.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3622=
4652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL2hvbWUvMjAyNDA3Mjg=
yMTYyOTcvZW4vUHJvcGVsLUZ1ZWxzJUUyJTgwJTk5cy1UcmFkZS1TZWNyZXQtVGhlZnQtQ2FzZS=
1BZ2FpbnN0LVBoaWxsaXBzLTY2LVNjaGVkdWxlZC1mb3ItVHJpYWwtQXVndXN0LTI2LTIwMjQ/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28ba4f7c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">there=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Propel Fuels, Inc. (=E2=80=9CPropel=E2=
=80=9D), a leading retailer of low-carbon fuels at stations throughout Cali=
fornia, shared today that its trade secret misappropriation case against Ph=
illips 66 Company (=E2=80=9CPhillips 66=E2=80=9D) has been scheduled for ju=
ry trial on August 26, 2024, in the Superior Court of California, County of=
 Alameda, located in Oakland, California.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
he lawsuit, filed on February 16, 2022, alleges that Philips 66 stole confi=
dential data, proprietary strategies and business intelligence developed by=
 Propel over 13 years at a cost to Propel of more than $200 million. ...</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to court filings, Propel and Philli=
ps 66 entered into due diligence in 2017 in connection with a proposed acqu=
isition of Propel by Phillips 66. Phillips 66 extended the due diligence pr=
ocess over eleven months, during which Propel, under a non-disclosure agree=
ment, disclosed its proprietary strategies and data, and was actively build=
ing a new integrated renewable fuels business for Phillips 66, when Phillip=
s 66 abruptly and without explanation terminated the deal on August 24, 201=
8.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next business day, Phillips 66 annou=
nced to California regulators that it would enter the E85 market in the sta=
te and launched retail sales of high-blend renewable diesel weeks later. Ph=
illips 66 rapidly expanded its California renewables business using Propel=
=E2=80=99s data and market insights; it now retails E85 or renewable diesel=
 at more than 600 stations in the state.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">If you=C2=A0<em>pretend</em> you are going to buy a competitor, =
they will give you lots of access to due diligence materials, and you can l=
earn a lot about their business. And then you can make an informed decision=
:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16p=
x 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">not to get into the business,</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">to get into the business by buying t=
hem, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">to get into the business y=
ourself,=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>buying them, but maybe using what you h=
ave learned.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, again, you might=C2=
=A0get sued =E2=80=94=C2=A0you had to sign a nondisclosure agreement to get=
 all of this information =E2=80=94 but again it can be hard to know what is=
=C2=A0protected confidential information and what is portable industry know=
ledge. From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/362246=
52.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcHAuYm94LmNvbS9zL2NkZmFmNjF2bWd5c2F4NmF0ODdoODQ2cHU1Z=
mJzbTRk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1ded3eda" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the lawsuit</a>:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Phillips 66 also required disclosure (=
also under the NDA) of the proprietary marketing, customer identification, =
customer retention, regulatory, carbon credit, pricing and other business s=
trategies that were the heart of Propel=E2=80=99s business. Those were cont=
ained in the materials provided to Phillips 66 through the data room and du=
e diligence responses, but also in confidential meetings with teams of Phil=
lips 66 executives who repeatedly visited Propel=E2=80=99s California headq=
uarters and other locations to study the business. Throughout, those execut=
ives expressed admiration for the Propel=E2=80=99s strategies and the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s ability to generate profits and high-volume sales in a market =
Phillips 66 thought was inaccessible.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The allegations are all about stealing=C2=A0<em>strategies</em>, bu=
siness ideas, not, like, product designs or secret manufacturing processes.=
 They are a bit fuzzy.=C2=A0Realistically any merger target faces this risk=
: that at the end of due diligence, the acquirer will just conclude =E2=80=
=9Cmeh we can do this ourselves, we don=E2=80=99t actually need them.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is one reason that being a merger =
target is=C2=A0<em>risky: </em>You can=E2=80=99t generally sell your busine=
ss without revealing a lot about the business to potential acquirers.<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent=
 !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> If you reveal a lot and then the deal doesn=E2=80=99t happen, that=E2=
=80=99s bad. It might be bad for simple signaling reasons: What you reveale=
d was bad, the potential acquirers fled, and now everyone knows that you ha=
ve a bad business. Or it might be bad for competitive reasons: What you rev=
ealed was good, so the potential acquirers took the best parts for themselv=
es.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMTgvamFuZS1zdHJlZXQtd2FudHMtaXRzLXNlY3JldHMtY=
mFjaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
