om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">More Left</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMjYvYW5kcmV3LWxlZnQtd2Fzbi10LXNob3J0LWZvci1s=
b25nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MjkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB74260379" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked</a> on Friday<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> about Andrew Left, the activist short seller=C2=A0who was charged with=
 securities fraud last week. The US Securities and Exchange Commission and =
Department of Justice alleged that Left frequently shorted stocks, publishe=
d research reports and tweets saying he was short, and then more or less im=
mediately covered his shorts: The stocks would drop on his tweets, and he w=
ould buy them back at a quick profit rather than waiting to see if his shor=
t reports were correct and the stocks stayed down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">As I wrote on Friday: That seems fine? I mean, it would be fine if =
Left was explicit about it, and also probably fine if he was, you know, <em=
>implicit</em> about it. Put some fine print in the reports saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe can cover at any time,=E2=80=9D leave it at that, take some profits. =
But what annoys the authorities is that Left allegedly=C2=A0<em>lied=C2=A0<=
/em>about it, telling people on Twitter and television that he was still sh=
ort even after he had covered.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can =
see why this would be=C2=A0annoying, and fraud. But it strikes me as=C2=A0a=
 secondary issue; to me, the primary issue is: Was he right? Like, if he pu=
blished short reports saying =E2=80=9CCompany X is a fraud,=E2=80=9D and th=
en the stock dropped, and then he covered his shorts, and then a few months=
 later Company X was shut down for fraud, then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I would be in=
clined to give him the benefit of the doubt? Even if he was lying about sti=
ll being short?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because I think the point h=
ere is that it=E2=80=99s securities fraud if he deceived people about some=
=C2=A0<em>material=C2=A0</em>fact. If people went around thinking =E2=80=9C=
I need to be in the same trades Andrew Left,=E2=80=9D and he said =E2=80=9C=
I shorted Company X and am still short right this minute and will stay shor=
t for months,=E2=80=9D and they believed him=C2=A0<em>about his position</e=
m>, so they=C2=A0shorted Company X, and actually he had already bought back=
 his short, then that would be fraud about a material fact.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">But I don=E2=80=99t think that happened? I think that happ=
ened is that people went around thinking =E2=80=9CAndrew Left has a good tr=
ack record of finding stocks to short,=E2=80=9D and he said =E2=80=9CCompan=
y X is a fraud and I am short,=E2=80=9D and they believed him=C2=A0<em>abou=
t Company X</em>, so they shorted Company X. And then if he was honest and =
diligent and mostly correct about Company X being a fraud, then, you know, =
kind of no harm no foul? Even if he covered his shorts immediately?</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not saying this is the law =E2=80=94=C2=A0I d=
on=E2=80=99t think it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just a statement of my=
 sympathies. And I have not closely studied his track record, and I don=E2=
=80=99t know how honest and diligent his calls actually were; again, the SE=
C has messages that suggest he might not have been all that honest and dili=
gent. But we did talk about one call, when Left decided to short a Canadian=
 cannabis company called Cronos Group in 2018. =E2=80=9CI have a hot voice =
in cannibas,=E2=80=9D Left told an associate; =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s take a=
 vantage [sic] of it.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So, says the SEC:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lat=
er that same day, Left published a report and sent a tweet to his readers r=
ecommending that they sell CRON and that the true valuation of the company =
was $3.50 per share: =E2=80=9C<em>$CRON tgt price $3.5. Everything that is =
contaminated about the Cannabis space. ALL HYPE with possible securities fr=
aud</em>.=E2=80=9D The tweet linked to the report which was titled, =E2=80=
=9C<em>Cronos: The Dark Side of The Cannabis Space.</em>=E2=80=9D</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Weirdly the SEC does not get into this, but Cronos closed at =
$12.74 per share on Aug. 29, 2018, the day before Left=E2=80=99s report. It=
 closed at $9.12 on Aug. 30, after the report came out, a 28% drop. It then=
 rallied, getting as high as $23.70 in March 2019. But then it mostly went =
down. It hit Left=E2=80=99s $3.50 price target in early 2022, and closed at=
 $2.42 yesterday. It has never reported an operating profit. It took a whil=
e, and many readers who shorted the stock presumably lost money, but was Le=
ft =E2=80=A6 right?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But someho=
w I missed that=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzcm9vbS9wcmVzcy1yZWxlYXNl=
cy8yMDIyLTE5MQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f720e4a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>the SEC charg=
ed Cronos with fraud=C2=A0</em>in 2022</a>. It=E2=80=99s not the biggest fr=
aud in the world, and it happened starting in 2019 (so after Left=E2=80=99s=
 report), but still. The SEC says that Left was committing fraud when he sa=
id that Cronos would go to $3.50 and might be committing securities fraud, =
even though Cronos went to $3.50 and (in the SEC=E2=80=99s view) committed=
=C2=A0securities fraud.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other poi=
nt. The SEC charges against Left allege that he basically did some pump-and=
-dumps (buy stocks, say misleading things to get others to buy them, sell i=
nto the demand), and =E2=80=94=C2=A0more characteristically, for a short se=
ller=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0some reverse pump-and-dumps (short stocks, say mis=
leading things to get others to sell them, buy into the demand). (The latte=
r trade is sometimes called =E2=80=9Cshort and distort,=E2=80=9D to have an=
other rhyme.) This is a very traditional thing to charge a media-happy inve=
stor with, and the SEC brings lots of cases like this.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But we did <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjQtMDMtMjEvcHVtcC1hbmQtZHVtcHMtYXJlLWxlZ2FsLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI5M=
jRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1f=
dGVybT0yNDA3MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc=
041dd6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">talk a few months ago</a> about a very weird case in Texas =
where a federal district judge ruled that actually pump-and-dumps are legal=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are not securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0because the go=
vernment can=E2=80=99t prove that the pump-and-dumper=C2=A0<em>deceived=C2=
=A0</em>the same people that he=C2=A0<em>took money=C2=A0</em>from. A pump-=
and-dumper tells lies about a stock to induce people to buy the stock, and =
then he sells the stock. But you can=E2=80=99t prove =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in =
fact it is unlikely =E2=80=94=C2=A0that he sells the stock=C2=A0<em>to=C2=
=A0</em>the people he lied to. Probably the pump-and-dumper sells stock to =
market makers, and his deceived readers buy stock from the market makers, s=
o the pump-and-dumper =E2=80=9Cdid not obtain something of value from the e=
ntity to be deceived=E2=80=9D and so did not defraud anyone.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">I wrote about the decision at the time, but I have tried =
not to think about it much since, because (1) it is obviously wrong but (2)=
 if you believe it, then pretty much=C2=A0<em>all </em>public-markets=C2=A0=
securities fraud is legal now,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0because all public-market securities fraud works like that: You n=
ever trade=C2=A0<em>directly=C2=A0</em>with the people you=E2=80=99re lying=
 to, so you can =E2=80=94=C2=A0on this theory =E2=80=94=C2=A0never defraud =
anyone. But a reader emailed to mention that case and ask =E2=80=9Cwhat is =
different about the two cases,=E2=80=9D and the answer is nothing. If that =
ruling is correct then nothing, including this, is fraud.</p><table class=
