treet has agreed to pay about $7.5 million to settle allegations a subsidia=
ry of the financial-services firm received payments and redacted invoices f=
rom two Russian entities that faced U.S. sanctions restrictions.=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The subsidiary, Charles River Development, a fi=
nancial technology company specializing in software for communicating tradi=
ng information, allegedly altered the dates and reissued invoices and accep=
ted contractual payments from two clients majority-owned by Russian banks S=
berbank or VTB Bank between 2016 and 2020, according to the U.S. Treasury D=
epartment=E2=80=99s Office of Foreign Assets Control.=C2=A0</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the Office of Foreign Asset Control <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36224652.222390/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9vZmFjLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9yZWNlbnQtYWN0aW9ucy8yMDI0MDcyNg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB8c7f2cb5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">announcement</a>. Charles River=C2=A0sells =
the FIX Network, a trading communications network. Between 2016 and 2020, s=
everal of its customers were Russian entities sanctioned by the US. Seems b=
ad, but apparently Charles River was=C2=A0<em>allowed=C2=A0</em>to provide =
services to those clients: They were sanctioned, but the sanctions did not =
prohibit them from buying software or services from Charles River, or Charl=
es River from selling to=C2=A0them. The actual business relationship=C2=A0w=
as fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, the <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly9vZmFjLnRyZWF=
zdXJ5Lmdvdi9tZWRpYS84Njk2L2Rvd25sb2FkP2lubGluZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b=
c6e6d9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">relevant sanctions</a> prohibited =E2=80=9Call transactions=
 in, provision of financing for, and other dealings in new debt of longer=
=E2=80=9D than a certain maturity (14, 30 or 90 days, depending on when the=
 debt was issued). Charles River was not trading bonds of sanctioned compan=
ies, or lending them money. But it=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>providing them so=
ftware and services, and sending them invoices. And then the Russian compan=
ies would pay the invoices. But if they paid more than 14 (or 30 or 90) day=
s after the invoice, then the payment was illegal: Charles River was extend=
ing them more credit than the sanctions allowed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">There is an obvious solution, and the Russian clients and Charles Riv=
er found it. From the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/36224652.222390/aHR0cHM6Ly9vZmFjLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9tZWRpYS85MzMwNzYvZG9=
